Survival Analysis: Acute-on-Chronic Kidney Disease in Cats¶

Wendy Hu¶

Final Project for UCLAX CSX4501

In this project, we analyze data relating to acute-on-chronic kidney disease (ACKD) in cats. We use exploratory data analysis to identify biological and environmental variables that are correlated or anti-correlated with survival times, build machine learning classifier models to predict survival at 100 days and 500 days after an acute kidney failure event, and test and compare model performance for 3 trained classifers. On test sets, the logistic regression classifier achieved on average 74% accuracy in predicting survival at 100 days and 80% accuracy in predicting survival at 500 days, and outperformed the histogram gradient boosting and support vector classifiers.

1. Introduction ¶

1.1 Background and motivation ¶

Chronic kidney disease (CKD) is extremely common in cats. Although it can occur at any feline life stage, the prevalence increases with age. By some estimates up to 30% of cats over age 10, and up to 80% of cats over age 15, have kidney disease. The illness is progressive and generally terminal (unless the cat passes away from another condition first, which is not uncommon in long-lived cats), though disease progression can be slowed significantly and cats can often enjoy high quality of life for long periods with proper treatment. However, early stage disease is usually subtle or asymptomatic, so the problem is often not diagnosed until advanced stages. In many cases, the diagnosis is not made until an acute crisis event occurs on top of the chronic condition, called acute-on-chronic kidney disease (ACKD), causing dramatic symptoms like severe lethargy/unresponsivenss, swelling, shortness of breath, or seizures or coma in severe cases. Because of already impaired kidney function from chronic illness, cats with CKD are at greater risk for sudden kidney injury triggered by an acute cause such as pyelonephritis (kidney infection), ureteral/urethral obstruction (kidney stones obstructing the flow of urine from the kidneys or bladder), cardiorenal syndrome (dysfunction of the heart inducing kidney dysfunction), or toxicity caused by various drug side effects or accidentally ingested toxins. Oftentimes the cause of the acute kidney injury is unknown or cannot be determined conclusively.

Although feline CKD has been extensively studied and categorized into well-defined stages with well-established treatment goals and prognoses at each stage, research and literature on the prognosis of ACKD is sparse despite it being a relatively common complication of CKD. During an exhaustive literature search, I found only 2 papers on the prognosis of ACKD. One of those papers was published relatively recently (2021) and the authors cite only one other paper published on this subject (also the only other paper I found during my search).

Because my cat recently experienced an ACKD crisis (and because a large number of people in the feline kidney disease support group I'm in also have cats who have experienced such crises), coupled with the sparsity of research into the prognosis of this condition, I am motivated to potentially contribute to the current knowledge on feline ACKD with my data analysis work.

1.2 Objective ¶

The objective is to perform exploratory data analysis on the dataset to identify important features that are correlated or anti-correlated to survival, and to build a machine learning model that can accurately predict survival times.

1.3 Dataset source ¶

The dataset used in this project is sourced from the raw data in the recent paper:

  • Renard J, Faucher MR, Combes A, Concordet D, Reynolds BS. 2021. Machine-learning algorithm as a prognostic tool in non-obstructive acute-on-chronic kidney disease in the cat. Journal of Feline Medicine and Surgery. 23(12):1140–1148. https://doi.org/10.1177/1098612x211001273

The authors in their paper also trained an ML classifier to predict survival outcomes, but the data processing, analysis, ML models, and performance testing used in my project is wholly independent of and does not at all overlap with the methods and analysis used in the paper. In addition, the paper focuses only on predicting short-term outcomes (survival at 7, 30, 90, and 180 days) whereas this project focuses on predicting longer-term outcomes (survival at 100 and 500 days).

A limitation of this dataset is that it is of very small size -- 46 data points in total. (I attempted to contact other researchers to obtain more raw data for this project, but ultimately was not successful). In later sections we will discuss the challenges and impacts on our data analysis posed by the small sample size and strategies for mitigation.

The columns in the dataset are:

  • Case (Case number assigned by the original study, with an asterick if the patient was excluded for missing data in the original study)
  • Breed
  • Sex
  • Neutered
  • Age (years)
  • Body Weight (kg)
  • Case Severity Score (A score ranging from 0-7 indicating the severity of clinical symptoms as observed by veterinarian at time of hospitalization)
  • Small Kidney (Number of the patient's kidneys that are abnormally small or atrophied as seen on ultrasound. 0=none, 1=1 kidney, 2=both kidneys)
  • Nephroliths (Presence or absence of kidney stones)
  • Creatine at 48 hours (mg/dl) (Blood creatine levels at 48 hours after hospitalization. Creatine is an important indicator of kidney function, and higher levels of creatine generally correlate with higher blood toxin levels and greater kidney function impairment)
  • Spontaneous Feeding at 48 hours (At time of hospitalization, cats are generally not eating or drinking during the acute crisis. After hospitalization for 48 hours, did they start eating?)
  • Aetiology (The diagnosed cause of the acute kidney injury leading to hospitalization. For the majority of patients in this dataset, the cause is unknown, indicated by NaN)
  • Survival (days) (Days survived after hospitalization)
  • Still alive at conclusion of study? (Whether the patient was still alive at publication time of the original study. If yes, indicates that the true survival time could potentially be much higher than the number of days currently stated in the "Survival" column)

In the next section, we will perform exploratory data analysis to understand the distributions in the dataset and identify features that may be correlated or anti-correlated with survival times.

We can see that sadly, most cats in the dataset survived only a very short amount of time -- half of the cats survived only one month or less, and the majority (75%) survived less than one year. However, there's clearly a strong right skew in this distribution with many outliers who had high survival time values, including one cat who survived over 5 years (and who was still alive at the conclusion of the study). In the next sections, we will perform exploratory data analysis to identify features that are correlated or anti-correlated with survival times.

2.3 "Naive" exploratory data analysis ¶

In this section we will perform a kind of "naive" analysis, and plot the quantitative and categorical features against the raw survival times given in the "Survival (days)" column. I call this analysis "naive" because many of the cats in the dataset were still alive at the conclusion of the original study, so their true survival time could potentially be much higher than the number of days indicated in the "Survival (days)" column. Nevertheless, this analysis should help reveal some general patterns and correlations present in the data.

2.3.1 Creatine¶

High creatine levels have a negative association with survival times. Although we can see a couple of outliers, in general cats who survived for any significant amount of time (longer than 6 months) had lower creatine levels at 48 hours (generally less than 6). High creatine levels above 6 generally had low survival times.

In [4]:
df[['Creatine at 48 hours (mg/dl)', 'Survival (days)']].plot(kind='scatter', x='Creatine at 48 hours (mg/dl)', y='Survival (days)')
plt.show()

2.3.2 Body weight¶

There seems to be a slightly negative association betwen body weight and survival times, with the majority of the long-lived (survival > 500 days) cats weighing less than 4kg.

In [5]:
df[['Body Weight (kg)', 'Survival (days)']].plot(kind='scatter', x='Body Weight (kg)', y='Survival (days)')
plt.show()

2.3.3 Case severity score¶

Surprisingly, the plots do not seem to reveal a very salient association between case severity scores (CSS) and survival times. Higher CSS of 6 or 7 seems to have lower average survival times, but otherwise no linear/monotonic association seems to be present. CSS of both 1 and 4 seem to have slightly higher average survival times than the other scores.

In [6]:
df[['Case Severity Score', 'Survival (days)']].plot(kind='scatter', x='Case Severity Score', y='Survival (days)')
plt.show()
df.boxplot(column='Survival (days)',by='Case Severity Score')
plt.ylabel('Survival (days)')
plt.show()

2.3.4 Age¶

There seems to be a negative association between age and survival times. The majority of cats who survived past one year were under age 12.

In [7]:
df[['Age (years)', 'Survival (days)']].plot(kind='scatter', x='Age (years)', y='Survival (days)')
plt.show()

2.3.5 Sex¶

There is a very strong association between sex and survival times, with female cats surviving significantly longer (mean: 407 days, median: 161 days) than male cats (mean: 107 days, median: 9 days). There are also roughly equal numbers of male and female cats in the dataset, so this association is not due to an artifact of small sample size.

2.3.7 Nephroliths¶

Confusingly, cats with nephroliths (kidney stones) have a higher median survival time, but lower mean survival time. As we will see in analyses in the future sections, cats who have kidney stones are more likely to survive to 100 days, but less likely to survive to 500 days. This phenomenon of increased short-term survival rates but decreased long-term survival rates may explain the difference between the mean and median values.

2.3.8 Aetiology¶

For the aetiology feature, the dataset shows only 3 different values: "Pyelonephritis" (kidney infection), "NaN" (unknown), and "Cardiorenal syndrome". To do exploratory analysis on this feature, we will first replace the "NaN" and "Cardiorenal syndrome" values with "Unknown or Other Aetiology".

2.3.9 Breed¶

For the breed feature, we can see from the dataset that only a small number of cats were breeds other than domestic shorthair (DSH) -- only 6 out of 46 cats were other breeds. Their individual breed categories are therefore not really useful, so before we do the data analysis we will replace these values with "Other Breed".

The DSH and breed cats have similar median survival times (30 days vs 38 days), however the mean survival time for DSH cats (282 days) is much higher than the mean survival time for the breed cats (191 days). This indicates that the survival time distribution for DSH cats is much more right skewed, and there are many more long-lived DSH cats than breed cats, as we can see from the histogram plot.

2.3.10 Spontaneous feeding at 48 hours¶

Cats who exhibited spontaneous feeding at 48 hours were significantly longer-lived (mean: 353 days, median: 53 days) than the cats who were not eating at that time (mean: 98 days, median: 0 days). We can also see from the histogram plot that nearly all cats who survived past 6 months were eating at 48 hours post-hospitalization.

2.3.11 Neutered¶

The dataset shows that only 3 cats out of 46 were not neutered. A sample this small is likely not useful for categorization or performing data analysis on, so we will ignore this feature.

2.3.12 Summary¶

After performing this "naive" analysis, we saw some general patterns.

For the quantitative features:

  • Higher values for creatine, body weight, and age were all associated with lower survival times

For the categorical features:

  • Females, cats with pyelonephritis, domestic short hair cats, and cats who fed spontaneously at 48 hours were longer-lived than cats not in those categories
  • Presence of nephroliths had a more complicated relationship with survival times: cats with kidney stones had higher median survival times but lower mean survival times
  • No monotonic relationship between case severity score and survival times could be discerned from the data

2.4 Exploratory data analysis, with categorization by 100 and 500 days survival ¶

Although the previous "naive" analysis revealed some general patterns, its reliability is limited because many of the longer-lived cats were still alive at the conclusion of the original study, and so many of the raw values obtained from "Survival (days)" column are likely to be inaccurate and possibly significantly lower than true survival times. In order to do data analysis and build an ML model with more reliability, we will do some pre-processing on the data and categorize the cats by survival to 100 days and 500 days, and then we will perform exploratory data analysis on these categories. The thresholds of 100 days and 500 days were chosen because these values seemed to be natural breaks in the data upon visual inspection of the survival times histogram plot.

2.4.1 Data pre-processing¶

We will add two columns to our dataset called 'Survived 100 days' and 'Survived 500 days' whose values are 'Yes', 'No', or 'NaN' (if unknown). Although we know the values for survival at 100 days for all cats in the dataset, we're careful to handle the case where survival at 500 days is unknown because the cat was still alive at the conclusion of the original study.

In [14]:
def survived_x_days(row, num_days):
    if row['Survival (days)'] < num_days and row['Still alive at conclusion of study?'] == 'No':
        return 'No'
    elif row['Survival (days)'] >= num_days:
        return 'Yes'
    else:
        return float('NaN')

def survived_100_days(row):
    return survived_x_days(row, 100)

def survived_500_days(row):
    return survived_x_days(row, 500)

df['Survived 100 days'] = df.apply (lambda row: survived_100_days(row), axis=1)
df['Survived 500 days'] = df.apply (lambda row: survived_500_days(row), axis=1)

df = df.drop(columns=['Case','Neutered','Survival (days)','Still alive at conclusion of study?'])

After doing the categorization by 100 days survived and 500 days survived, we will drop the columns "Survival (days)" and "Still alive at conclusion of study?" since they will not be used in subsequent analyses. In addition, we will drop the columns "Case" and "Neutered" since they are not useful to our analysis.

from pandas.api.types import is_numeric_dtype

def plot_survival_comparison_for_num_days(variable_name, num_days):
    num_days_str = ' ' + str(num_days) + ' days'
    survival_category_title = 'Survived' + num_days_str
    survived = df.loc[df[survival_category_title] == 'Yes', variable_name]
    not_survived = df.loc[df[survival_category_title] == 'No', variable_name]
    plt.hist([survived, not_survived], label=[survival_category_title, 'Did not survive' + num_days_str])
    plt.xlabel(variable_name)
    plt.ylabel('Number of cats')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    if is_numeric_dtype(df[variable_name]):
        df.boxplot(column=variable_name,by=survival_category_title)
        plt.ylabel(variable_name)
        plt.show()
        print(df.groupby(survival_category_title)[variable_name].describe())
    else : 
        print(df.groupby(variable_name)[survival_category_title].value_counts())

def plot_survival_comparison(variable_name):
    num_days = [100, 500]
    for y in num_days: 
        plot_survival_comparison_for_num_days(variable_name, y)

2.4.13 Summary¶

We gleaned some important insights into survival patterns from this categorical comparison analysis.

For the quantitative features:

  • Higher values for age, case severity score, and creatine levels were associated with significantly lower survival rates at 100 days, with the effect being even more pronounced at 500 days
  • Average body weight did not differ in a statistically significant way between those who survived and those who did not survive to 100 and 500 days

For the categorical features:

  • Cats with pyelonephritis and those who fed spontaneously at 48 hours had significantly higher survival rates at 100 days, with the effect being even more pronounced at 500 days, than cats not in those categories
  • Females, domestic short-hairs, and cats with one small kidney had higher survival rates at 100 and 500 days than cats not in those categories
  • Presence of nephroliths had a more complicated relationship with survival times: kidney stones were associated with higher survival rates at 100 days but lower survival rates at 500 days

3. Building an ML classifier for predicting survival at 100 days and 500 days ¶

We will now use the features we've analyzed to build classifiers for predicting survival.

3.1 Choosing a classifier ¶

To start, we will choose the histogram gradient boosting classifier, which is an ensemble learning algorithm based on boosting weak decision tree learners. We choose this classifier because of its native support for both quantitative and categorical features, as well as its native support for handling missing values in the dataset (we have a very small dataset with quite a few missing values, and would like to avoid excluding rows).

3.2 Data pre-processing ¶

First, we need to do some data pre-processing. We encode the values for all the categorical features, transforming text values into integers representing each category. Additionally, we create new dataframes separating the target columns from the feature columns, and drop rows with unknown target values.

In [29]:
# Categorical feature encodings
df['Small Kidney'] = df['Small Kidney'].astype(int)
df['Sex'] = df['Sex'].replace({'M':1, "F":0})
df['Breed'] = df['Breed'].replace({'DSH':0, 'Other Breed':1})
df['Nephroliths'] = df['Nephroliths'].replace({'Yes':1, 'No':0})
df['Spontaneous Feeding at 48 hours'] = df['Spontaneous Feeding at 48 hours'].replace({'Yes':1, 'No':0})
df['Aetiology'] = df['Aetiology'].replace({'Pyelonephritis':1, 'Unknown or Other Aetiology':0})
df['Survived 100 days'] = df['Survived 100 days'].replace({'Yes':1, 'No':0})
df['Survived 500 days'] = df['Survived 500 days'].replace({'Yes':1, 'No':0})

# Drop rows without target value, and separate target columns from feature columns
df_500_days_classifier = df[df['Survived 500 days'].notnull()]
features_500_days = df_500_days_classifier.drop(['Survived 500 days', 'Survived 100 days'], axis=1)
target_500_days = df_500_days_classifier['Survived 500 days']
features_100_days = df.drop(['Survived 500 days', 'Survived 100 days'], axis=1)
target_100_days = df['Survived 100 days']

The algorithm always predicts negative values, no matter what! It's evil and always wants cats to die! 😱 What's going on?

Actually it turns out that this is a common problem, when training classifiers with "imbalanced classes" -- that is, where the dataset has many more samples for one class than for another. During training, the classifier essentially figures out that it can achieve very high accuracy by simply always predicting the majority class. Since the majority of cats in our dataset sadly did not survive to 500 days, the classifier can achieve high accuracy by always predicting non-survival. In the next section, we'll employ an over-sampling strategy to build a better, less pessimistic classifier.

3.4 Dealing with imbalanced classes: over-sampling, and shuffle inputs ¶

We'll use a strategy called over-sampling to resolve our problem of imbalanced classes causing the classifier to only predict the majority class. With this strategy, we randomly select and duplicate rows from our minority class and add them to our training set, in order to get equal numbers of samples in all classes for our classifier to train on. Usually, the opposite strategy of under-sampling from majority class is used, and over-sampling from the minority class is rarely employed in practice. However, because of the already small size of our dataset, in this case we are likely to get much better results from over- rather than under-sampling. Note that we first do the train-test split before over-sampling the training data, to make the test set "fair", so that we're not inadvertently using as test samples potentially over-sampled duplicates from the training data. However, this means that the distribution of classes in the test set will be very different from the distribution in the training set. This may impact the prediction results and limit the accuracy of our classifier, which we will discuss in later sections.

In addition to over-sampling from the minority class for training data, we will also shuffle the training data samples. This may also help build a better classifier because some classification algorithms can perform poorly during training if given long sequences of one class, and get "stuck" during gradient descent.

We'll create some helper functions to help us perform minority class over-sampling and input shuffling during model training and testing:

In [32]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
from sklearn.utils import shuffle
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'

def train_classifier(features, target, test_size, random_state, classifier):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=test_size, shuffle=True, random_state=random_state)

    over_sampler = RandomOverSampler(sampling_strategy='auto', random_state=0)
    X_train, y_train = over_sampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

    model = classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
    return model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test

def train_and_test_classifier(features, target, test_size, random_state, printResults, classifier, label=None):
    model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_classifier(features, target, test_size, random_state, classifier)
    
    training_score = model.score(X_train, y_train)
    test_score = model.score(X_test, y_test)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    y_score = model.decision_function(X_test)
    
    confusion_matrix = sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    classification_report = sklearn.metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_pred, zero_division=0)
    
    if printResults:
        print('Results for ' + label + ' classifier:')
        print('Training Score:', training_score)
        print('Test Score:', test_score)
        print("Confusion matrix: \n" + str(confusion_matrix))
        print("Classification report: \n" + str(classification_report))
    return model, training_score, test_score, y_test, y_score, y_pred

That test score is not so great.

Clearly, there's a wide variability in the training and test scores we could get from our classifier, depending on the how the random train-test split works out. Because of our very small sample size, sometimes we can get a very unlucky train-test split and perform quite poorly on testing (or alternatively get very lucky and perform unusually well on the test set). In the next section, we'll employ a "batch testing" strategy to test the performance of our classifier in a more reliable way.

4. Testing Classifier Performance ¶

4.1 Re-thinking how to test model performance: batch testing ¶

Because of our very small sample size, we can encounter a very wide range of test scores depending the specific (random) train-test split we end up with. This is obviously unideal, so we need a better way of measuring the performance of our classifier in a reproducible, reliable way. We will implement "batch testing" where we will train and test the classifier 100 times, each with a different random seed for the train-test split. This will hopefully (if the randomization algorithm is decent) generate a wide variety of different train-test splits that will provide a representative sampling from the distribution of all possible train-test splits (and test scores). We'll then look to the summary statistics of the distribution of test scores from batch testing to evaluate the true performance of our classifier. We'll also combine the predictions of the classifier over all iterations to generate an aggregated ROC curve and classification report.

First we'll create some helper functions to help us perform the batch testing:

In [35]:
import numpy as np

def flatten_list(nested_list):
    return [item for sublist in nested_list for item in sublist]

def batch_test_classifier(features, target, test_size, classifier, label, plotResults=True, plotRocCurve=True, rocCurveAx=None):
    training_scores = []
    test_scores = []
    y_true_values = []
    y_score_values = []
    y_pred_values = []

    # train and test classifier 100 times
    for i in range(100):
        model, training_score, test_score, y_true, y_score, y_pred = train_and_test_classifier(features, target, test_size, i, False, classifier, label)
        training_scores.append(training_score)
        test_scores.append(test_score)
        y_true_values.append(y_true)
        y_score_values.append(y_score)
        y_pred_values.append(y_pred)
    
    # aggregate predicted, true, and probability score values over all iterations
    y_true_values_aggregated = flatten_list(y_true_values)
    y_score_values_aggregated = flatten_list(y_score_values)
    y_pred_values_aggregated = flatten_list(y_pred_values)
    
    if plotResults:
        print('Training and Test Scores Results for ' + label + ' with ' + str(classifier) + ':')
        training_test_scores_df = pd.DataFrame(np.array([training_scores, test_scores]).transpose(), columns=['Training Scores', 'Test Scores'])
        training_test_scores_df.boxplot()
        plt.show()

        plt.hist(training_test_scores_df, label=['Training Scores', 'Test Scores'])
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()
        
        confusion_matrix = sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(y_true_values_aggregated, y_pred_values_aggregated)
        classification_report = sklearn.metrics.classification_report(y_true_values_aggregated, y_pred_values_aggregated, zero_division=0)
        print("Confusion matrix: \n" + str(confusion_matrix))
        print("Classification report: \n" + str(classification_report))
    
    if plotRocCurve:
        roc_curve = sklearn.metrics.RocCurveDisplay.from_predictions(y_true_values_aggregated, y_score_values_aggregated, ax=rocCurveAx, name=str(classifier))
    
    return training_scores, test_scores

4.4 "Sanity test": check prediction consistency rate between the two classifiers ¶

Another way we can evaluate the reliability of our two classifiers is to perform a simple "sanity test": how consistent are the predictions between our 100 days survival classifier and our 500 days survival classifier? That is, if the 500 days survival classifier predicts survival at 500 days, then to be logically consistent the 100 days survival classifier should also predict survival at 100 days. If the 100 days survival classifier predicts non-survival at 100 days, then for logical consistency the 500 days survival classifier should also predict non-survival at 500 days. The two classifiers were independently trained so logical consistency is not guaranteed, thus a high consistency rate between the two classifiers would be another signal that our classifiers have learned some true underlying data patterns.

We will again employ batch testing because any specific iteration may produce widely varying values depending on the specific random train-test split, due to our small sample size.

In [38]:
def is_prediction_consistent(prediction_100_days, prediction_500_days):
    if prediction_100_days == 0 and prediction_500_days == 1: 
        return False
    else : 
        return True

def get_consistency_rate_for_model_predictions(y_pred_100, y_pred_500):
    total_count = y_pred_100.size
    inconsistent_prediction_count = 0
    for i in range(total_count):
        if is_prediction_consistent(y_pred_100[i], y_pred_500[i]) == False : 
            inconsistent_prediction_count += 1
    return 1 - (inconsistent_prediction_count / total_count)

def test_classifier_consistency(random_state):
    model_100, _, X_test, _, _ = train_classifier(features_100_days, target_100_days, 0.2, random_state, HistGradientBoostingClassifier())
    model_500, _, _, _, _ = train_classifier(features_500_days, target_500_days, 0.2, random_state, HistGradientBoostingClassifier())
    y_pred_100 = model_100.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_500 = model_500.predict(X_test)
    return get_consistency_rate_for_model_predictions(y_pred_100, y_pred_500)

5.2 Other ML classifiers: logistic regression and support vector classifier ¶

We'll test the logistic regression and support vector classifier (SVC) and see if these algorithms outperform our previous histogram gradient boosting classifier. Logistic regression was chosen because of its ability to model non-linear variables well, and SVC was chosen because of its purported ability to perform well on small datasets.

5.2.1 Data pre-processing: missing values imputation ¶

Unlike the histogram gradient boosting classifier, the logistic regression and support vector classifiers do not accept missing values for features. So we will first need to impute any missing data. Since all the missing values in the dataset are for quantitative features, we will use the simple strategy of replacing them with the median values of those columns.

In [41]:
def impute_values_for_features(features):
    features_with_imputed_values = features.copy()
    features_with_imputed_values['Age (years)'].fillna(df['Age (years)'].median(), inplace=True)
    features_with_imputed_values['Case Severity Score'].fillna(df['Case Severity Score'].median(), inplace=True)
    features_with_imputed_values['Creatine at 48 hours (mg/dl)'].fillna(df['Creatine at 48 hours (mg/dl)'].median(), inplace=True)
    return features_with_imputed_values

features_500_days_with_imputed_values = impute_values_for_features(features_500_days)

6. Conclusions, discussion, and future work ¶

On test sets, the logistic regression classifier outperformed both the histogram gradient boosting and support vector classifiers, achieving on average 74% accuracy in predicting survival at 100 days and 80% accuracy in predicting survival at 500 days. However, these decent overall accuracy scores hide a high number of false positives and low precision for the positive class, which may be due to the use of over-sampling in our training set (which was a necessity because of imbalanced classes and small dataset size). In addition, average test scores are significantly lower than training scores, possibly also due to limited data. It's very clear that for future iterations of these classifiers, the most important enhancement that would be most likely to improve classification accuracy is simply to get more data.

Other possible iterative improvements:

  • Tweaking the prediction threshold for the classifier models to possibly favor precision over recall. It would be interesting to research and evaluate the tradeoffs and impacts on classification accuracy
  • Normalizing quantitative features to a constant mean and standard deviation, which sometimes can improve model performance
  • Using regularization. My minor experiments with regularization seemed to always decrease test scores, but there may be more systematic ways to use regularization in models that may help us pinpoint an optimal value
  • Implementing k-fold cross-validation rather than my version of "batch testing" and observe any differences. I suspect that with a dataset as small as this one, even k-fold cross-validation may potentially end up with some highly "unlucky" training or test sets that may skew performance results.

After doing this data analysis work, I also have some unanswered questions which deserve further scrutiny:

  • Why are the AUC values for the ROC curve of the support vector classifier higher than the other classifiers, but its test scores lower than the other classifiers? What does AUC represent mathematically, and how does it relate to prediction accuracy?
  • Why do we see variability for the minimum test scores for each classifier with batch testing? This cannot be explained by differences in standard deviation, because these are roughly similar across classifiers.
  • Is there a way to extract data from the learned ML models such that insights can be gleaned about the dataset features, and allow the learned model parameters to be interpretable?

I'm greatly intrigued by the challenges and questions posed by this project. In the hopes of answering these questions and gaining a deeper understanding of the statistical and machine learning tools used in this project and throughout this class, I will be taking a graduate class next semester called "The Mathematics of Machine Learning" which covers statistical learning theory and provable guarantees for ML models. I look forward to deepening my knowledge and improving my data science and ML skillset.
